EPISTLE VL—AD NUMICIUM.

'Phe moral of this epistle may be in part represented by Milton’s line Comus, 210),— ( ’ ‘ These thoughts may startle well, but not astound ‘ The virtuous mind.’

It opens with a proverb from the Greek, which in its original meaning denoted the characteristic fearlessness of the well-balanced mind, free from amazement or superstitious alarm at natural phenomena; but which might be, and here is, brought to bear upon moral causes of disquietude as well. These are the admiration and desire of wealth and power, of popular distinc- tions (vv. 5—-14; 17—23)‚ the real value of which is tested by Time and Death (vv. 24—27.) True wisdom is never in excess (v. 16> ; the real excellence os life is found in virtue (v. 30„ if not, let a man indulge his bent without re- spect to virtue ; enrich himself without scruple as to means (υ. 32, sqq.) ς gratify his ambition as he will (v. 49, sqq. ), or his luxury (v. 56, sqq.)
